<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/QuantityKindDimensionVector_Imperial> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/QuantityKindDimensionVector> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/QuantityKindDimensionVector_SI> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/QuantityKindDimensionVector_SI> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy> <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/QuantityKindDimensionVector_SI> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Quantity Kind Dimension vector (SI)"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/QuantityKindDimensionVector_SI> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/QuantityKindDimensionVector> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/QuantityType> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/QuantityType> <http://purl.org/dc/terms/description> "\n  A $\\textit{Quantity Type}$ is an enumeration of quantity kinds. \n  It specializes $\\boxed{dtype:EnumeratedValue}$ by constrinaing $\\boxed{dtype:value}$ to instances of $\\boxed{qudt:QuantityKind}$.\n  "^^<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/LatexString> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/QuantityType> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy> <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/QuantityType> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Quantity type"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/QuantityType> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/EnumeratedValue> .
_:autos479 <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Restriction> .
_:autos479 <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#allValuesFrom> <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/QuantityKind> .
_:autos479 <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#onProperty> <http://www.linkedmodel.org/schema/dtype#value> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/QuantityType> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> _:autos479 .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/QuantityValue> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/QuantityValue> <http://purl.org/dc/terms/description> "\n  <p>A <em>Quantity Value</em> \n  </p>"^^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/QuantityValue> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy> <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/QuantityValue> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Quantity value"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/QuantityValue> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/Concept> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/QuantityValue> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/Quantifiable> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/QuantityValue> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/Verifiable> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/RatioScale> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/RatioScale> <http://purl.org/dc/terms/description> "\n  <p>A <em>Ratio Scale</em> possesses a meaningful (unique and non-arbitrary) zero value. \n  Most measurement in the physical sciences and engineering is done on ratio scales. \n  Examples include mass, length, duration, plane angle, energy and electric charge.\n  </p>\n  <p>In contrast to interval scales, ratios are now meaningful because having a non-arbitrary zero point makes it meaningful to say,\n   for example, that one object has \"twice the length\" of another (= is \"twice as long\"). \n  Very informally, many ratio scales can be described as specifying \"how much\" of something (i.e. an amount or magnitude) or \"how many\" (a count). \n  The Kelvin temperature scale is a ratio scale because it has a unique, non-arbitrary zero point called absolute zero.\n  </p>"^^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/RatioScale> <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/informativeReference> "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Level_of_measurement"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#anyURI> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/RatioScale> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy> <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/RatioScale> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Ratio scale"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/RatioScale> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#seeAlso> <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/IntervalScale> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/RatioScale> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#seeAlso> <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/NominalScale> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/RatioScale> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#seeAlso> <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/OrdinalScale> .
<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/RatioScale> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/Scale> .
